result.execSummary:
The defendant Keelan Anthony Gilbertson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person, in custody, with Attorney Prior.  Defendant plead no contest to obstructing, repeater enhanser struck.  Court advised the elements and possible penalties in the count the defendant plead to.  He understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights with the defendant.  Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Obstructing an Officer, contrary to 946.41(1).  Joint recommendation for:  90 days jail.  CC.  Attorney Prior says defendant has served 12 days on this case.  No more jail time warranted.  

Court ordered:  30 days jail.  CC.  Credit for 12 days.  Pay CC @ $25/mo starting 6/1.    Failure to pay any part of the fine or court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.
